t political institutions are more flexible and less centralized than their Soviet counterparts were.Shirk pioneers a rational choice institutional approach to analyze policy-making in a non-democratic authoritarian country and to explain the history of Chinese market reforms from 1979 to the present. Drawing on extensive interviews with high-level Chinese officials, she pieces together detailed histories of economic reform policy decisions and shows how the political logic of Chinese communist institutions shaped those decisions.Combining theoretical ambition with the flavor of on-the-ground policy-making in Beijing, this book is a major contribution to the study of reform in China and other communist countries.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aHISTORY / Asia / General.2bisacsh  a20th century chinese policy.  aasian history.  aauthoritarian.  abeijing.  acalifornia series on social choice and political economy.  achina.  achinese communist institutions.  achinese history.  acommunism.  acommunist rule.  aeconomic market reform.  aeconomic policy.  aeconomic reform policy.  aeconomic reform.  aeconomics.  afiscal decentralization.  agovernment and governing.  aleadership.  aparticularism.  apolicy making.  apolitical institutions.  apolitics.  aprice reform.  aprofit contracting.  areciprocal accountability.  areform.  asoviet union.  atax for profit.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052007707240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520912212?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520912212423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520912212/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  